The important thing to understand about Bittensor is that it's not like hashrate mining.  Once you have gotten the infrastructure software (Bittensor) installed, the miner or validator codebase is going to be different depending on which subnet(s) you're working in.  There is a very general checklist for preparing to mine or validate here: https://docs.bittensor.com/subnets/checklist-for-validating-mining but it does not contain step-by-step instructions for any particular model or version of node software, which will be subnet-specific.

You can explore the different subnets through the channels in the Subnet and Testnet categories of this Discord. If you have any questions about what equipment/resources/knowledge is required in a particular subnet, check the pinned posts in the subnet's channel.

Note that because the code is different in each subnet, and trying to accomplish something different, it means that there is not really going to be an easy way for us to recommend subnets for newcomers, or for specific computer specifications, etc.  It'll be up to you to figure out which one(s) best match your equipment, resources, and skill level, if you are interested in exploring further. : )

# How can I get started mining/validating?

The important thing to understand about Bittensor is that it's not like hashrate mining.  Once you have gotten the infrastructure software (Bittensor) installed, the miner or validator codebase is going to be different depending on which subnet(s) you're working in.  There is a very general overview of mining in Bittensor here: https://docs.bittensor.com/miners/ and of validating here: https://docs.bittensor.com/validators/ but these documents don't include step-by-step instructions for any particular model or version of node software, which will be subnet-specific.

You can explore the different subnets through the channels in the Subnet and Testnet categories of this Discord. If you have any questions about what equipment/resources/knowledge is required in a particular subnet, check the pinned posts in the subnet's channel.

Note that because the code is different in each subnet, and trying to accomplish something different, it means that there is not really going to be an easy way for us to recommend subnets for newcomers, or for specific computer specifications, etc.  It'll be up to you to figure out which one(s) best match your equipment, resources, and skill level, if you are interested in exploring further. : )

The important thing to understand about Bittensor is that it's not like hashrate mining.  Once you have gotten the infrastructure software (Bittensor) installed, the miner or validator codebase is going to be different depending on which subnet(s) you're working in, and there is no minimum configuration that will work for all subnets.  There is a very general overview of mining in Bittensor here: https://docs.bittensor.com/miners/ and of validating here: https://docs.bittensor.com/validators/ but these documents don't include step-by-step instructions for any particular model or version of node software, which will be subnet-specific.

You can explore the different subnets through the channels in the Subnet and Testnet categories of this Discord. If you have any questions about what equipment/resources/knowledge is required in a particular subnet, check the pinned posts in the subnet's channel.

Note that because the code is different in each subnet, and trying to accomplish something different, it means that there is not really going to be an easy way for us to recommend subnets for newcomers, or for specific computer specifications, etc.  It'll be up to you to figure out which one(s) best match your equipment, resources, and skill level, if you are interested in exploring further. : )

Some of the issues that people have with importing mnemonic phrases include:

o Having a leading space in front of the first word, or a trailing space after the last work

o Pasting in a phrase that uses something other than a space to separate the words

o Hidden/non-printing characters in the phrase (especially when copying and pasting)

o Extended ASCII characters -- for example, if you regularly use a keyboard that incorporates extended ASCII characters for a language other than English, if those characters are in the phrase, it will probably cause the application to not be able to recognize the phrase

o Words in the wrong order (if you wrote it down in rows, but then try to enter it in columns, or vice versa)

o Misspelling the words -- see the master BIP-39 word list to confirm spellings: https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0039/english.txt

# How can I get started mining/validating?

The important thing to understand about Bittensor is that it's not like hashrate mining.  Once you have gotten the infrastructure software (Bittensor) installed, the miner or validator codebase is going to be different depending on which subnet(s) you're working in.  There is a very general overview of mining in Bittensor here: https://docs.bittensor.com/miners/ and of validating here: https://docs.bittensor.com/validators/ but these documents don't include step-by-step instructions for any particular model or version of node software, which will be subnet-specific.

You can explore the different subnets through the channels in the Subnet and Testnet categories of this Discord. If you have any questions about what equipment/resources/knowledge is required in a particular subnet, check the pinned posts in the subnet's channel.

Note that because the code is different in each subnet, and trying to accomplish something different, it means that there is not really going to be an easy way for us to recommend subnets for newcomers, or for specific computer specifications, etc.  It'll be up to you to figure out which one(s) best match your equipment, resources, and skill level, if you are interested in exploring further. : )

-=-=-=-=-=-
